Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of bed, he put on his combat uniform, his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, being particularly careful with a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything he needed. After checking his ammunition pockets, he quietly left the barracks, the sound of mud and ice crunching under his boots.
He took a lighter from his vest pocket and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small puff before slowly opening the door. The week before, he had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He stopped using the pre-set alarm, half the time it didn't work, as all that came out of the speakers was a faint whistle.
"You wake them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic arriving on foot.
"Ouep", replied Cohren.
"What do you plan to use this time?"
Before he could respond, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" Cohren asked.
"Well, primo, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up with today. Secundo, the first shock troops up are the first to breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," Cohren said. He extended his hand and flipped a switch. An alarm blared inside the barracks, loud and ear-piercing. He heard commotion inside and agitation.
"Good grief, Valturi," Nemic exclaimed. "We could have thought they would have learned to get up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here made sure to," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But, once again, their squad and section leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company was pouring out en masse. Everyone had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Good morning everyone," Cohren said cheerfully.
"Excuse me, sir, why do you insist on waking us up in this way?" one of the squad members, a corporal, asked.
"Because standard wake-ups are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't sleep in," Cohren replied.
"Make sure you have all your personal belongings," he continued. As the first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to conduct final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
The members of Company Exodus dispersed. They were part of the Second Division of Shock Troops, Second Army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being merged. It was a split company, and Cohren didn't know what to think about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that motivated it.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the many lights of the advanced operational base, powered by generators. Most of them were painted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel attacks, both in the air and on the ground, to fight them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are we being sent?"
"An advanced operational base outside of Ianlos. We were sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, taking a drag on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to smoking, but a year of combat changes a man, and he remained silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," Nemic muttered. "All the news coming from that place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' Why not send aid to the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," Cohren said, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're leaving with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Shaw got us a transport?", Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"Ouep. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "To all units of Company Exodus, report to the west vehicle park when you're done. We're leaving with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the platoon leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they arrived here. All four were very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like a long time ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were then platoon leaders. But Craith now commanded the second platoon for a week, after the previous commander's demobilization due to being wounded by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked towards the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked towards them, his usually cold face reflecting no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
